{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1781556964,"nonce":"L9nBUnvBNJ8aknGQxGABFuOm+xs=","message":"Add a third residual found while fixing the keyword list (PR review of the offline transform): **n-ary AND/OR flattening**.\n\nPostgreSQL deparses an associative chain of three or more operands flat:\n`a AND b AND c` -\u003e `(a AND b AND c)`, whereas the renderer builds binary AST nodes\nand emits `((a AND b) AND c)`. So a desired predicate `(((active = true) AND (status = 1)) AND (\"position\" IS NULL))`\nchurns against the introspected `((active = true) AND (status = 1) AND (\"position\" IS NULL))`.\n\nThis is another structural normalization the offline string transform cannot do (like the literal\ncasts) and is exactly what the semantic-AST-diff approach above handles for free: parse both sides,\nflatten/normalize, compare. The offline canonicalizer (PR for 3a5766f) therefore only guarantees\nidempotence for single comparisons / null checks and two-operand AND/OR chains.","files":null}]}